    "summary": "The construction of the Roman Colosseum (Flavian Amphitheatre, 70–80 AD) — covered in related form by [[event:2020|colosseum_construction]] — was the greatest feat of Roman construction engineering and the largest amphitheater ever built, capable of seating 50,000–80,000 spectators for gladiatorial combat, animal hunts (venationes), public executions, and staged naval battles. The Colosseum was built on the site of Nero's private lake, using the wealth from Titus's conquest of Jerusalem (70 AD) — the gold and silver looted from the [[event:2016|Temple of Jerusalem]] literally funded Rome's greatest entertainment venue.\n\nThe Colosseum's engineering innovations included a sophisticated underground system (the hypogeum) of tunnels, chambers, and elevators that could raise animals and gladiators dramatically to the arena floor; a retractable awning (velarium) supported by poles around the top ring that could shade the audience; and a complex ticketing and crowd-management system with numbered entrances and seating sections by social class. The building used an estimated 100,000 cubic meters of travertine stone, significant quantities of Roman concrete, brick, and tuff, fastened together with approximately 300 tons of iron clamps. The Colosseum remained in active use for over 400 years, hosting approximately 400,000 human deaths (gladiators, prisoners, criminals, and Christians according to later tradition) and over one million animal deaths. It remains the most visited ancient monument in the world.",
